Outliers


Outliers have an extreme value. How to deal with an outlier depends on why the observation stands out. Outliers can be

removed
corrected
ignored

The statistic \(R^2\) measures the proportion of variation in the data that is explained by the model.
\[
\begin{align*}
R^2
& = 1-\dfrac{SSR}{SST}\\
& = \dfrac{SST-SSR}{SST} \\
& = \dfrac{\text{var. explained by model}}{\text{total var.}}
\end{align*}
\]

Outliers, leverage and influential points

outliers: observations that fall far from the cloud of points;
high leverage points: observations that fall horizontally away from the cloud of points;
influential points: observations that influence the slope of the regression line;



All influential points are high leverage points.
All leverage points are outliers.
(Venn Diagram)

Function to compute \(R^2\)

compute_R2 <- function(model){

  model_glanced <- glance(model)
  R2 <- model_glanced$r.squared
  R2_rounded <- round(R2, 3) 

  return(R2_rounded)

}

Step 1: training and test sets
The following R function splits a sample into a training and a test set

construct_training_test <- function(sample, prop_training = 2/3){

  n          <- nrow(sample)
  n_training <- round(n * prop_training)

  sample_random   <- slice_sample(sample, n = n)
  sample_training <- slice(sample_random,    1 : n_training )
  sample_test     <- slice(sample_random, - (1 : n_training))

  return(list(
    training = sample_training, test = sample_test
    ))

}

Function to compute the RMSE

compute_RMSE <- function(test_set, model){

  y     <- test_set$Volume
  y_hat <- predict(model, test_set)

  E    <- y - y_hat
  SSE  <- sum(E^2)
  MSE  <- mean(E^2)
  RMSE <- sqrt(MSE)

  return(RMSE)

}
